  "prompt": "Is Kyiv (Kiev) radioactive?",
  "response": "Kyiv (Kiev), the capital of Ukraine, is not considered radioactive in a way that poses a significant health risk to its residents. However, it is worth noting a few points related to radioactivity in the region:\n\n1. **Chernobyl Exclusion Zone**: Kyiv is located approximately 100 kilometers (62 miles) south of the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant, which suffered a catastrophic meltdown in 1986. The areas immediately surrounding Chernobyl were heavily contaminated, and an exclusion zone was established. However, Kyiv itself was not directly in the path of the most severe radioactive fallout.\n\n2. **Monitoring and Safety**: Since the Chernobyl disaster, there has been continuous monitoring of radiation levels in Kyiv and throughout Ukraine. The Ukrainian government, along with international organizations, regularly assesses the environmental impact and ensures that radiation levels remain within safe limits.\n\n3. **Background Radiation**: Like any city, Kyiv has natural background radiation, which is normal and not harmful. The levels of background radiation in Kyiv are comparable to those found in many other parts of the world.\n\nIn summary, while Kyiv is near the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone, the city itself is not considered dangerously radioactive. Regular monitoring ensures that any potential risks are managed and communicated to the public.",
